00

What is Seaborn?

Seaborn is a Python statistical visualization library built on top of Matplotlib. It provides a high-level interface for drawing attractive, informative statistical graphics. Its key advantages over raw Matplotlib are automatic aggregation, confidence intervals, faceting, and beautiful default themes.

FeatureSeabornRaw Matplotlib
Statistical aggregationAutomatic (mean, CI, etc.)Manual
Faceting / multi-plot gridsBuilt-in (FacetGrid, relplot)Manual plt.subplots
Hue / style / size encodingSingle parameterManual loop + legend
Themes5 styles + 20+ palettesrcParams only
Relationship to MatplotlibReturns Axes objects — fully customizable—

Key rule: Every Seaborn function returns a Matplotlib Axes (or Figure/Grid for figure-level functions). You can always follow up with standard ax.set_*() calls.

Two levels of API

LevelFunctionsReturnsUse when
Axes-levelscatterplot, histplot, boxplot, …AxesYou control the Figure layout yourself
Figure-levelrelplot, displot, catplot, lmplotFacetGridYou need faceting / multi-plot grids

Installation & Setup

shell
pip install seaborn
# seaborn also installs matplotlib, numpy, pandas, scipy
pythonstandard imports
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np

print(sns.__version__)   # 0.13.x

# Apply a theme globally (recommended first step)
sns.set_theme(style="darkgrid", palette="deep")

# Built-in datasets (when internet available)
tips     = sns.load_dataset("tips")
iris     = sns.load_dataset("iris")
penguins = sns.load_dataset("penguins")
flights  = sns.load_dataset("flights")

Built-in datasets

02

Themes & Styles

Seaborn ships with five built-in styles that control the axes background and gridlines, plus context presets that scale element sizes for different outputs.

python
# Apply a style globally
sns.set_theme(style="darkgrid")      # sets everything
sns.set_style("whitegrid")           # style only

# Available styles
# "darkgrid" | "whitegrid" | "dark" | "white" | "ticks"

# Temporarily override
with sns.axes_style("white"):
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    sns.scatterplot(data=tips, x="total_bill", y="tip", ax=ax)
    plt.show()

# Context: scale text and line sizes for different output contexts
sns.set_context("talk")         # paper | notebook | talk | poster
sns.set_context("notebook", font_scale=1.2)

# Reset to defaults
sns.reset_defaults()
▶ output

set_theme() — one-call configuration

python
sns.set_theme(
    style="whitegrid",      # axes style
    palette="deep",         # color palette
    context="notebook",     # size context
    font="serif",           # font family
    font_scale=1.1,          # scale all text
    rc={"axes.spines.right": False,  # extra rcParams
        "axes.spines.top":   False}
)

Color Palettes

python
# View a palette
sns.color_palette("deep")           # returns list of RGB tuples

sns.set_palette("pastel")

# Use in a single call
sns.scatterplot(data=tips, x="total_bill", y="tip",
                hue="sex", palette="Set2")

# Custom palette dict (maps category → color)
pal = {"Male": "#4080ff", "Female": "#ff4060"}
sns.boxplot(data=tips, x="day", y="total_bill", hue="sex", palette=pal)

04

scatterplot

sns.scatterplot() is the axes-level function for scatter plots. It supports hue, style, and size encoding simultaneously — each backed by a separate legend.

pythonbasic + encoded
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 5))

# Basic
sns.scatterplot(data=tips, x="total_bill", y="tip", ax=axes[0])

# Multi-encoding
sns.scatterplot(
    data=tips, x="total_bill", y="tip",
    hue="sex",        # color by sex
    style="smoker",   # marker shape by smoker
    size="size",      # marker area by party size
    sizes=(25, 180),  # min/max marker area
    alpha=0.75,
    ax=axes[1]
)
plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()
▶ output

Key parameters

ParameterDescription
hueColumn name for color encoding — automatic legend + palette
styleColumn name for marker shape encoding
sizeColumn name for marker area encoding
sizesTuple (min, max) marker area in points²
paletteColor palette for hue — string name, list, or dict
alphaTransparency 0–1 (helps with overplotting)
markersList or dict of marker styles for style
legend'auto', 'brief', 'full', False
05

lineplot

sns.lineplot() aggregates data automatically — it computes the mean per x-value and draws a 95% confidence interval band by default.

python
# Single line — auto mean + CI
sns.lineplot(data=fmri, x="timepoint", y="signal")

# Multiple groups
sns.lineplot(
    data=fmri, x="timepoint", y="signal",
    hue="event",        # separate line per event type
    style="region",     # different linestyle per region
    errorbar="ci",      # "ci" | "sd" | "se" | "pi" | None
    n_boot=200,         # bootstrap samples for CI
    linewidth=2
)
plt.show()
▶ output

Auto-aggregation: lineplot groups by x (and by hue/style if given) and computes mean ± CI. To plot raw data without aggregation, pass estimator=None and ensure each (x, hue) combination is unique.

06

relplot — Faceted Relational

sns.relplot() is the figure-level function that wraps scatterplot and lineplot inside a FacetGrid. Use col= and row= to create multi-panel figures automatically.

python
g = sns.relplot(
    data=tips,
    x="total_bill", y="tip",
    hue="sex",
    col="time",       # panel per unique value of time
    row="smoker",    # row per unique value of smoker
    kind="scatter",  # "scatter" (default) | "line"
    height=3,         # height of each facet in inches
    aspect=1.1,       # width = height × aspect
    alpha=0.7
)
# g is a FacetGrid — access underlying figure and axes
g.fig.suptitle("My title", y=1.02)
g.set_axis_labels("Total Bill ($)", "Tip ($)")
plt.show()
▶ output

g.axes is a 2-D NumPy array of Axes objects — iterate with g.axes.flat to customize individual panels.

07

histplot

sns.histplot() replaces the old distplot. It supports count histograms, density, 2D bivariate histograms, and optional KDE overlay.

python
# Count histogram
sns.histplot(data=tips, x="total_bill", bins=25)

# Hue + KDE overlay
sns.histplot(data=tips, x="total_bill",
             hue="sex", kde=True, bins=22,
             alpha=0.65)

# 2D bivariate histogram (heatmap-style)
sns.histplot(data=tips, x="total_bill", y="tip",
             cbar=True)     # adds a colorbar
plt.show()
▶ output

histplot key parameters

ParameterDescription
binsNumber of bins or 'auto'
binwidthWidth of each bin (alternative to bins)
stat'count' (default), 'frequency', 'probability', 'density'
kdeOverlay KDE curve on top of histogram
cumulativeCumulative histogram
element'bars', 'step', 'poly' — bar shape
multiple'layer', 'dodge', 'stack', 'fill' — hue grouping
08

kdeplot

sns.kdeplot() draws a kernel density estimate — a smoothed histogram. Supports 1D and 2D (bivariate) versions.

python
# 1D with fill
sns.kdeplot(data=tips, x="total_bill",
            fill=True, alpha=0.4, linewidth=2)

# Multiple groups
sns.kdeplot(data=tips, x="total_bill",
            hue="sex", fill=True, alpha=0.3,
            linewidth=2)

# 2D bivariate KDE (contour plot)
sns.kdeplot(data=tips, x="total_bill", y="tip",
            cmap="Blues", fill=True,
            levels=8, thresh=0.05)
plt.show()
▶ output

kdeplot parameters

ParameterDescription
bw_adjustBandwidth multiplier — lower = more detail, higher = smoother
fillFill under the curve
levelsNumber of contour levels for 2D KDE
threshLowest contour level as fraction of max density (0–1)
cutExtend curve beyond data range by this many bandwidths
cumulativePlot cumulative distribution
09

ecdfplot

The empirical cumulative distribution function (ECDF) plot shows the proportion of data values at or below each x value — no binning required.

python
# Single ECDF
sns.ecdfplot(data=tips, x="total_bill")

# Grouped by day
sns.ecdfplot(data=tips, x="total_bill",
             hue="day", linewidth=2)

# Complementary ECDF (1 - CDF)
sns.ecdfplot(data=tips, x="total_bill",
             complementary=True)
plt.show()
▶ output

ECDF has no smoothing or binning choices — it is a direct non-parametric estimate of the distribution. It is especially useful for comparing groups without assuming a shape.

10

boxplot

sns.boxplot() draws box-and-whisker plots. In Seaborn 0.13+, pass a column to hue instead of using the old palette-without-hue pattern.

python
# Single grouping
sns.boxplot(data=tips, x="day", y="total_bill",
            hue="day", legend=False,
            palette="Set2")

# With additional hue grouping
sns.boxplot(data=tips, x="day", y="total_bill",
            hue="sex",
            palette={"Male": "#4080ff", "Female": "#ff4060"})
plt.legend()
plt.show()
▶ output

Box plot anatomy reminder

ElementMeaning
BoxIQR (Q1 to Q3 — middle 50% of data)
Line inside boxMedian (Q2)
WhiskersQ1 − 1.5×IQR to Q3 + 1.5×IQR
Fliers (dots beyond whiskers)Outliers
widthBox width (default 0.8)
fliersizeOutlier marker size (set 0 to hide)
11

violinplot

Violin plots combine a box plot with a kernel density estimate on each side, showing the full distribution shape.

python
# Standard violin
sns.violinplot(data=tips, x="day", y="total_bill",
               inner="box")   # "box" | "quart" | "point" | "stick" | None

# Split violin — compares two groups back to back
sns.violinplot(data=tips, x="day", y="total_bill",
               hue="sex", split=True,
               inner="quart")   # quartile lines inside violin
plt.show()
▶ output

split=True mirrors the two hue distributions on either side of the violin — ideal for direct comparison of two groups across categories.

12

boxenplot & stripplot

boxenplot (letter-value plot) extends the box plot with more quantile levels — great for large datasets. stripplot shows every raw data point.

python
# boxenplot — more quantile boxes for large data
sns.boxenplot(data=penguins, x="species", y="body_mass_g",
              hue="species", legend=False)

# stripplot — raw data points, dodged by group
sns.stripplot(data=penguins, x="species", y="body_mass_g",
              hue="sex", dodge=True, jitter=True,
              alpha=0.6, size=4)
plt.show()
▶ output
13

swarmplot

swarmplot positions non-overlapping dots so every data point is visible — a beeswarm chart. Best for N < 500.

python
# Pure swarm
sns.swarmplot(data=iris, x="species", y="petal_length",
              size=4)

# Box + swarm overlay (best practice for small datasets)
ax = sns.boxplot(data=iris, x="species", y="petal_length",
                 width=0.5, fliersize=0,
                 boxprops={"alpha": 0.35},
                 whiskerprops={"alpha": 0.35},
                 medianprops={"color": "white", "linewidth": 2})
sns.swarmplot(data=iris, x="species", y="petal_length",
              size=3.5, alpha=0.85, ax=ax)
plt.show()
▶ output
14

barplot & pointplot

Both show a statistical estimate per group. barplot uses bar height; pointplot uses a dot + connecting line — better for showing trends.

python
# barplot — mean + 95% CI error cap
sns.barplot(data=tips, x="day", y="total_bill",
            hue="day", legend=False,
            capsize=0.12, err_kws={"linewidth": 1.5},
            estimator="mean")    # or "median", np.std, …

# pointplot — trend across groups
sns.pointplot(data=tips, x="day", y="total_bill",
              hue="sex", dodge=True,
              capsize=0.12, markers=["o", "s"],
              linestyles=["-", "--"])
plt.show()
▶ output
15

countplot

countplot is a bar chart of category frequencies — equivalent to barplot with estimator=len.

python
# Count per day
sns.countplot(data=tips, x="day")

# Count per day, split by sex
sns.countplot(data=tips, x="day", hue="sex")

# Horizontal (swap x for y)
sns.countplot(data=tips, y="day", hue="smoker")

# Add value labels on each bar
ax = sns.countplot(data=tips, x="day", hue="sex")
ax.bar_label(ax.containers[0])
ax.bar_label(ax.containers[1])
plt.show()
▶ output

heatmap

sns.heatmap() takes a 2-D DataFrame and draws a color-encoded grid — perfect for correlation matrices, pivot tables, and confusion matrices.

python
# Annotated pivot table
flights_pivot = flights.pivot(index="month", columns="year", values="passengers")
sns.heatmap(flights_pivot, annot=True, fmt="d",
            cmap="YlOrRd", linewidths=0.3)

# Triangular correlation heatmap
corr = df.corr()
mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(corr, dtype=bool))  # hide upper triangle
sns.heatmap(corr, annot=True, fmt=".2f",
            cmap="coolwarm", center=0,
            mask=mask, linewidths=0.5)
plt.show()
▶ output

heatmap key parameters

ParameterDescription
annotAnnotate each cell with its value
fmtFormat string for annotation: 'd', '.2f', '.0%'
cmapColormap name
centerValue to center diverging colormap at (e.g. 0 for correlations)
vmin / vmaxClip colormap range
maskBoolean DataFrame — True cells are not drawn
linewidthsWidth of cell separator lines
squareForce square cells
18

clustermap

sns.clustermap() adds hierarchical clustering dendrograms to a heatmap, reordering rows and columns so similar patterns are adjacent.

python
g = sns.clustermap(
    flights_pivot.astype(float),
    cmap="YlOrRd",
    annot=True, fmt=".0f",
    annot_kws={"size": 7},
    linewidths=0.3,
    figsize=(9, 8),
    method="ward",           # linkage method: ward | average | complete
    metric="euclidean",      # distance metric
    z_score=1                 # standardize along axis 1 (columns)
)
# Turn off row/col clustering independently
g = sns.clustermap(flights_pivot, col_cluster=False)
plt.show()
▶ output
19

pairplot & PairGrid

pairplot plots all variable pairs in a dataset. The diagonal shows univariate distributions; off-diagonal cells show scatter (or other) plots.

python
# Quick pairplot — scatter off-diagonal, KDE diagonal
sns.pairplot(iris, hue="species",
             diag_kind="kde",
             plot_kws={"alpha": 0.6},
             diag_kws={"fill": True})

# PairGrid — full manual control
g = sns.PairGrid(iris, hue="species")
g.map_upper(sns.scatterplot, alpha=0.6)   # above diagonal
g.map_lower(sns.kdeplot)                   # below diagonal
g.map_diag(sns.histplot, kde=True)        # diagonal
g.add_legend()
plt.show()
▶ output

pairplot only works with numeric columns (plus an optional hue column). Drop non-numeric columns or select them explicitly with vars=['col1','col2',...].

jointplot & JointGrid

jointplot shows the joint distribution of two variables plus their marginal distributions.

python
# Regression + marginals
sns.jointplot(data=tips, x="total_bill", y="tip",
              kind="reg",         # scatter | kde | hex | reg | resid | hist
              height=5.5)

# Hue — multiple groups
sns.jointplot(data=penguins, x="bill_length_mm", y="body_mass_g",
              hue="species", height=5.5)

# JointGrid — full manual control
g = sns.JointGrid(data=tips, x="total_bill", y="tip")
g.plot_joint(sns.scatterplot, alpha=0.5)
g.plot_marginals(sns.histplot, kde=True)
plt.show()
▶ output
▶ output
kind=Joint plot type
'scatter'Scatter plot (default)
'kde'Bivariate KDE contours
'hist'2D histogram
'hex'Hexbin plot
'reg'Scatter + regression line + CI
'resid'Regression residuals

regplot & lmplot

regplot is the axes-level regression function. lmplot is the figure-level version that supports faceting.

python
# regplot — axes-level
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2)
sns.regplot(data=tips, x="total_bill", y="tip",
            ax=axes[0],
            scatter_kws={"alpha": 0.5},
            line_kws={"color": "red"})

# Polynomial regression
sns.regplot(data=tips, x="total_bill", y="tip",
            ax=axes[1], order=2)   # 2nd degree polynomial
plt.show()

# lmplot — figure-level with faceting
sns.lmplot(data=tips, x="total_bill", y="tip",
           hue="smoker", col="time",
           height=4, aspect=1.0)
plt.show()
▶ output
▶ output
22

residplot

residplot plots regression residuals vs the predictor — useful for checking if the regression assumptions hold (residuals should be random around 0).

python
sns.residplot(data=tips, x="total_bill", y="tip",
              lowess=True)   # overlay a LOWESS smoothed trend
plt.axhline(0, color="red", linewidth=1.5, linestyle="--")
plt.title("Regression residuals")
plt.show()

# If residuals show a pattern → model is misspecified
# Random scatter around 0 → model fits well

Both regplot and residplot are shown together above under S21.

FacetGrid (manual)

FacetGrid is the engine behind relplot, catplot, and lmplot. Using it directly gives you full control.

python
# Build grid
g = sns.FacetGrid(tips, col="time", row="sex",
                  height=3.5, aspect=1.2)

# Map any plotting function onto all panels
g.map_dataframe(sns.histplot, x="total_bill",
                kde=True, bins=20)

# Customize labels and titles
g.set_axis_labels("Total Bill ($)", "Count")
g.set_titles(template="{row_name} | {col_name}")

# Add a legend
g.add_legend()

# Access individual axes
g.axes[0, 0].set_title("Custom title")

plt.show()
▶ output
24

Despine & Utilities

python
# Remove top and right spines (cleaner look)
ax = sns.scatterplot(data=tips, x="total_bill", y="tip")
sns.despine()                  # removes top + right
sns.despine(left=True)         # also remove left spine
sns.despine(offset=8)          # offset axes from data
sns.despine(trim=True)         # trim spines to data range

# Move legend outside the axes
sns.move_legend(ax, "upper left",
                bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1),
                title="Sex")

# Get / set axis labels on a FacetGrid
g.set_axis_labels("x label", "y label")
g.set_titles(template="{col_name}")

# Color utility functions
sns.set_palette("deep")
sns.color_palette("viridis", 6)   # returns list of RGB tuples
sns.palplot(sns.color_palette())   # display palette as swatch
▶ output
25

Integration with pandas & Matplotlib

Seaborn accepts any pandas DataFrame or Series, and its axes-level functions return Matplotlib Axes — so standard Matplotlib customization always works.

python
# Seaborn axes-level → returns Axes → customise with matplotlib
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 4))
sns.boxplot(data=tips, x="day", y="total_bill", ax=ax)

# Standard matplotlib calls
ax.set_title("Bills by Day", fontsize=14)
ax.set_xlabel("Day of week")
ax.set_ylabel("Bill ($)")
ax.axhline(20, color="red", linestyle="--", label="$20 threshold")
ax.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("plot.png", dpi=150, bbox_inches="tight")
plt.show()

# Figure-level → access via .fig and .axes
g = sns.relplot(data=tips, x="total_bill", y="tip")
g.fig.suptitle("Suptitle on FacetGrid", y=1.02)
g.set_axis_labels("Bill", "Tip")
for ax in g.axes.flat:
    ax.set_ylim(0, 12)
plt.show()

Figure-level vs axes-level: Figure-level functions (relplot, catplot, displot, lmplot) do not accept an ax= argument — they create their own Figure. Use axes-level functions when embedding into an existing subplot layout.

26

Common Pitfalls

PitfallSymptomFix
Passing ax= to figure-level functionTypeErrorUse axes-level equivalent (scatterplot, not relplot)
Palette without hue (v0.13+)FutureWarningAssign hue=x and set legend=False instead
Data not tidy (wide format)Unexpected plot / errorsMelt to long format: df.melt(id_vars=[...], var_name='variable')
Old distplotAttributeErrorReplace with histplot (+ optional kde=True)
Missing plt.show() in scriptsNo outputAdd plt.show() at end of script (not needed in Jupyter)
FacetGrid not saving fullyClipped title/legendUse g.savefig("out.png", bbox_inches='tight') on the grid object
errwidth / ci deprecatedFutureWarning in v0.13Replace ci=95 → errorbar='ci', errwidth=2 → err_kws={'linewidth':2}
Large datasets in swarmplotSlow / overlappingUse stripplot (faster) or sample data first

Tidy data — the golden rule

python
# ❌ Wide format — does NOT work with hue
df_wide = pd.DataFrame({
    "Male":   [10, 12, 15],
    "Female": [9,  11, 14],
})

# ✅ Long (tidy) format — works with hue="sex"
df_long = df_wide.melt(var_name="sex", value_name="tip")
sns.boxplot(data=df_long, x="sex", y="tip", hue="sex")

Exercise 1 — Iris scatter + KDE

Plot iris sepal_length vs sepal_width as a scatter (hue+style by species) and petal_length as a KDE by species, side by side.

pythonanswer
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(12, 5))

sns.scatterplot(data=iris, x="sepal_length", y="sepal_width",
                hue="species", style="species",
                s=60, alpha=0.8, ax=axes[0])
axes[0].set_title("Sepal dimensions by species")

sns.kdeplot(data=iris, x="petal_length", hue="species",
            fill=True, alpha=0.35, linewidth=2, ax=axes[1])
axes[1].set_title("Petal length distribution")

sns.despine()
plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()

Exercise 3 — Pivot heatmap

Group tips by day and time, compute mean total_bill, pivot, and display as an annotated heatmap.

pythonanswer
pivot = (tips.groupby(["day", "time"])["total_bill"]
             .mean().unstack())

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 4))
sns.heatmap(pivot, annot=True, fmt=".1f",
            cmap="YlOrRd", linewidths=0.5, ax=ax)
ax.set_title("Mean total bill by day × time")
sns.despine()
plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()

Exercise 4 — Penguin distribution dashboard

Create a 2×2 figure: violin of flipper length, strip of bill depth by sex, histogram+KDE of body mass, and correlation heatmap.

pythonanswer
fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 9))

sns.violinplot(data=penguins, x="species", y="flipper_length_mm",
               hue="species", inner="box", legend=False, ax=axes[0,0])
axes[0,0].set_title("Flipper length by species")

sns.stripplot(data=penguins, x="species", y="bill_depth_mm",
              hue="sex", dodge=True, jitter=True, alpha=0.7,
              size=4, ax=axes[0,1])
axes[0,1].set_title("Bill depth by species + sex")

sns.histplot(data=penguins, x="body_mass_g", hue="species",
             kde=True, bins=25, alpha=0.65, ax=axes[1,0])
axes[1,0].set_title("Body mass distribution")

corr = penguins[["bill_length_mm","bill_depth_mm",
                 "flipper_length_mm","body_mass_g"]].corr()
sns.heatmap(corr, annot=True, fmt=".2f", cmap="coolwarm",
            center=0, linewidths=0.5, ax=axes[1,1])
axes[1,1].set_title("Correlation heatmap")

sns.despine()
fig.suptitle("Penguin Dashboard", fontsize=14, y=1.01)
plt.tight_layout(); plt.show()
